# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: foundation-fieldbus
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] A **distributed control system** (**DCS**) is a computerized control system for a process or plant usually with many control loops, in which autonomous controllers are distributed throughout the system, but there is no central operator supervisory control.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] This is in contrast to systems that use centralized controllers; either discrete controllers located at a central control room or within a central computer.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The DCS concept increases reliability and reduces installation costs by localizing control functions near the process plant, with remote monitoring and supervision.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Distributed control systems first emerged in large, high value, safety critical process industries, and were attractive because the DCS manufacturer would supply both the local control level and central supervisory equipment as an integrated package, thus reducing design integration risk.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Today the functionality of Supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) and DCS systems are very similar, but DCS tends to be used on large continuous process plants where high reliability and security is important, and the control room is not necessarily geographically remote.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Many machine control systems exhibit similar properties as plant and process control systems do.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The key attribute of a DCS is its reliability due to the distribution of the control processing around nodes in the system.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] This mitigates a single processor failure.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] If a processor fails, it will only affect one section of the plant process, as opposed to a failure of a central computer which would affect the whole process.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] This distribution of computing power local to the field Input/Output (I/O) connection racks also ensures fast controller processing times by removing possible network and central processing delays.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The accompanying diagram is a general model which shows functional manufacturing levels using computerised control.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Levels 1 and 2 are the functional levels of a traditional DCS, in which all equipment are part of an integrated system from a single manufacturer.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Levels 3 and 4 are not strictly process control in the traditional sense, but where production control and scheduling takes place.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The processor nodes and operator graphical displays are connected over proprietary or industry standard networks, and network reliability is increased by dual redundancy cabling over diverse routes.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] This distributed topology also reduces the amount of field cabling by siting the I/O modules and their associated processors close to the process plant.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The processors receive information from input modules, process the information and decide control actions to be signalled by the output modules.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The field inputs and outputs can be analog signals e.g.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] 4–20 mA DC current loop or two-state signals that switch either "on" or "off", such as relay contacts or a semiconductor switch.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] DCSs are connected to sensors and actuators and use setpoint control to control the flow of material through the plant.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] A typical application is a PID controller fed by a flow meter and using a control valve as the final control element.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The DCS sends the setpoint required by the process to the controller which instructs a valve to operate so that the process reaches and stays at the desired setpoint.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Large oil refineries and chemical plants have several thousand I/O points and employ very large DCS.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Processes are not limited to fluidic flow through pipes, however, and can also include things like paper machines and their associated quality controls, variable speed drives and motor control centers, cement kilns, mining operations, ore processing facilities, and many others.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] DCSs in very high reliability applications can have dual redundant processors with "hot" switch over on fault, to enhance the reliability of the control system.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Although 4–20 mA has been the main field signalling standard, modern DCS systems can also support fieldbus digital protocols, such as Foundation Fieldbus, profibus, HART, modbus, PC Link, etc.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Modern DCSs also support neural networks and fuzzy logic applications.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Recent research focuses on the synthesis of optimal distributed controllers, which optimizes a certain H-infinity or the H 2 control criterion.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Distributed control systems (DCS) are dedicated systems used in manufacturing processes that are continuous or batch-oriented.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Process control of large industrial plants has evolved through many stages.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Initially, control would be from panels local to the process plant.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] However this required a large amount of human oversight to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The next logical development was the transmission of all plant measurements to a permanently-staffed central control room.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Effectively this was the centralisation of all the localised panels, with the advantages of lower manning levels and easier overview of the process.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Often the controllers were behind the control room panels, and all automatic and manual control outputs were transmitted back to plant.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] However, whilst providing a central control focus, this arrangement was inflexible as each control loop had its own controller hardware, and continual operator movement within the control room was required to view different parts of the process.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] With the coming of electronic processors and graphic displays it became possible to replace these discrete controllers with computer-based algorithms, hosted on a network of input/output racks with their own control processors.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] These could be distributed around plant, and communicate with the graphic display in the control room or rooms.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The distributed control system was born.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The introduction of DCSs allowed easy interconnection and re-configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and easy interfacing with other production computer systems.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Early minicomputers were used in the control of industrial processes since the beginning of the 1960s.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The IBM 1800, for example, was an early computer that had input/output hardware to gather process signals in a plant for conversion from field contact levels (for digital points) and analog signals to the digital domain.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The first industrial control computer system was built 1959 at the Texaco Port Arthur, Texas, refinery with an RW-300 of the Ramo-Wooldridge Company.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] In 1975, both HONEYWELL and Japanese electrical engineering firm Yokogawa introduced their own independently produced DCS's - TDC 2000 and CENTUM systems, respectively.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] US-based Bristol also introduced their UCS 3000 universal controller in 1975.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] In 1978 Valmet introduced their own DCS system called Damatic (latest web-based generation Valmet DNAe).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] In 1980, Bailey (now part of ABB) introduced the NETWORK 90 system, Fisher Controls (now part of Emerson Electric) introduced the PROVoX system, Fischer & Porter Company (now also part of ABB) introduced DCI-4000 (DCI stands for Distributed Control Instrumentation).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The DCS largely came about due to the increased availability of microcomputers and the proliferation of microprocessors in the world of process control.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Computers had already been applied to process automation for some time in the form of both direct digital control (DDC) and setpoint control.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] In the early 1970s Taylor Instrument Company, (now part of ABB) developed the 1010 system, Foxboro the FOX1 system, Fisher Controls the DC2 system and Bailey Controls the 1055 systems.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] All of these were DDC applications implemented within minicomputers (DEC PDP-11, Varian Data Machines, MODCOMP etc.) and connected to proprietary Input/Output hardware.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Sophisticated (for the time) continuous as well as batch control was implemented in this way.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] A more conservative approach was setpoint control, where process computers supervised clusters of analog process controllers.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] A workstation provided visibility into the process using text and crude character graphics.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Availability of a fully functional graphical user interface was a way away.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Central to the DCS model was the inclusion of control function blocks.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Function blocks evolved from early, more primitive DDC concepts of "Table Driven" software.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] One of the first embodiments of object-oriented software, function blocks were self-contained "blocks" of code that emulated analog hardware control components and performed tasks that were essential to process control, such as execution of PID algorithms.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Function blocks continue to endure as the predominant method of control for DCS suppliers, and are supported by key technologies such as Foundation Fieldbus today.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Midac Systems, of Sydney, Australia, developed an objected-oriented distributed direct digital control system in 1982.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The central system ran 11 microprocessors sharing tasks and common memory and connected to a serial communication network of distributed controllers each running two Z80s.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The system was installed at the University of Melbourne.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Digital communication between distributed controllers, workstations and other computing elements (peer to peer access) was one of the primary advantages of the DCS.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Attention was duly focused on the networks, which provided the all-important lines of communication that, for process applications, had to incorporate specific functions such as determinism and redundancy.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] As a result, many suppliers embraced the IEEE 802.4 networking standard.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] This decision set the stage for the wave of migrations necessary when information technology moved into process automation and IEEE 802.3 rather than IEEE 802.4 prevailed as the control LAN.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] In the 1980s, users began to look at DCSs as more than just basic process control.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] A very early example of a Direct Digital Control DCS was completed by the Australian business Midac in 1981–82 using R-Tec Australian designed hardware.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The system installed at the University of Melbourne used a serial communications network, connecting campus buildings back to a control room "front end".
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Each remote unit ran two Z80 microprocessors, while the front end ran eleven Z80s in a parallel processing configuration with paged common memory to share tasks and that could run up to 20,000 concurrent control objects.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] It was believed that if openness could be achieved and greater amounts of data could be shared throughout the enterprise that even greater things could be achieved.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The first attempts to increase the openness of DCSs resulted in the adoption of the predominant operating system of the day: *UNIX*.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] UNIX and its companion networking technology TCP-IP were developed by the US Department of Defense for openness, which was precisely the issue the process industries were looking to resolve.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] As a result, suppliers also began to adopt Ethernet-based networks with their own proprietary protocol layers.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The full TCP/IP standard was not implemented, but the use of Ethernet made it possible to implement the first instances of object management and global data access technology.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The 1980s also witnessed the first PLCs integrated into the DCS infrastructure.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Plant-wide historians also emerged to capitalize on the extended reach of automation systems.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The first DCS supplier to adopt UNIX and Ethernet networking technologies was Foxboro, who introduced the I/A Series system in 1987.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The drive toward openness in the 1980s gained momentum through the 1990s with the increased adoption of commercial off-the-shelf (COTS) components and IT standards.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Probably the biggest transition undertaken during this time was the move from the UNIX operating system to the Windows environment.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] While the realm of the real time operating system (RTOS) for control applications remains dominated by real time commercial variants of UNIX or proprietary operating systems, everything above real-time control has made the transition to Windows.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The introduction of Microsoft at the desktop and server layers resulted in the development of technologies such as OLE for process control (OPC), which is now a de facto industry connectivity standard.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Internet technology also began to make its mark in automation and the world, with most DCS HMI supporting Internet connectivity.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The 1990s were also known for the "Fieldbus Wars", where rival organizations competed to define what would become the IEC fieldbus standard for digital communication with field instrumentation instead of 4–20 milliamp analog communications.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The first fieldbus installations occurred in the 1990s.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Towards the end of the decade, the technology began to develop significant momentum, with the market consolidated around Ethernet I/P, Foundation Fieldbus and Profibus PA for process automation applications.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Fieldbus technics have been used to integrate machine, drives, quality and condition monitoring applications to one DCS with Valmet DNA system.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The impact of COTS, however, was most pronounced at the hardware layer.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] For years, the primary business of DCS suppliers had been the supply of large amounts of hardware, particularly I/O and controllers.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The initial proliferation of DCSs required the installation of prodigious amounts of this hardware, most of it manufactured from the bottom up by DCS suppliers.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Standard computer components from manufacturers such as Intel and Motorola, however, made it cost prohibitive for DCS suppliers to continue making their own components, workstations, and networking hardware.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] As the suppliers made the transition to COTS components, they also discovered that the hardware market was shrinking fast.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] COTS not only resulted in lower manufacturing costs for the supplier, but also steadily decreasing prices for the end users, who were also becoming increasingly vocal over what they perceived to be unduly high hardware costs.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The traditional DCS suppliers introduced new generation DCS System based on the latest Communication and IEC Standards, which resulting in a trend of combining the traditional concepts/functionalities for PLC and DCS into a one for all solution—named "Process Automation System" (PAS).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The gaps among the various systems remain at the areas such as: the database integrity, pre-engineering functionality, system maturity, communication transparency and reliability.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] While it is expected the cost ratio is relatively the same (the more powerful the systems are, the more expensive they will be), the reality of the automation business is often operating strategically case by case.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The current next evolution step is called Collaborative Process Automation Systems.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] To compound the issue, suppliers were also realizing that the hardware market was becoming saturated.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The life cycle of hardware components such as I/O and wiring is also typically in the range of 15 to over 20 years, making for a challenging replacement market.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Many of the older systems that were installed in the 1970s and 1980s are still in use today, and there is a considerable installed base of systems in the market that are approaching the end of their useful life.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Developed industrial economies in North America, Europe, and Japan already had many thousands of DCSs installed, and with few if any new plants being built, the market for new hardware was shifting rapidly to smaller, albeit faster growing regions such as China, Latin America, and Eastern Europe.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Because of the shrinking hardware business, suppliers began to make the challenging transition from a hardware-based business model to one based on software and value-added services.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] It is a transition that is still being made today.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The applications portfolio offered by suppliers expanded considerably in the '90s to include areas such as production management, model-based control, real-time optimization, plant asset management (PAM), Real-time performance management (RPM) tools, alarm management, and many others.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] To obtain the true value from these applications, however, often requires a considerable service content, which the suppliers also provide.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Increasingly, and ironically, DCS are becoming centralised at plant level, with the ability to log into the remote equipment.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] This enables operator to control both at enterprise level ( macro ) and at the equipment level (micro), both within and outside the plant, because the importance of the physical location drops due to interconnectivity primarily thanks to wireless and remote access.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] The more wireless protocols are developed and refined, the more they are included in DCS.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] DCS controllers are now often equipped with embedded servers and provide on-the-go web access.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Whether DCS will lead Industrial Internet of Things (IIOT) or borrow key elements from remains to be seen.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] Many vendors provide the option of a mobile HMI, ready for both Android and iOS.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/distributed-control-system] With these interfaces, the threat of security breaches and possible damage to plant and process are now very real.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] A **fieldbus** is a member of a family of industrial digital communication networks used for real-time distributed control.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Fieldbus profiles are standardized by the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) as IEC 61784/61158.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] A complex automated industrial system is typically structured in hierarchical levels as a distributed control system (DCS).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In this hierarchy the upper levels for production managements are linked to the direct control level of programmable logic controllers (PLC) via a non-time-critical communications system (e.g.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The fieldbus links the PLCs of the direct control level to the components in the plant at the field level, such as sensors, actuators, electric motors, console lights, switches, valves and contactors.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] It also replaces the direct connections via current loops or digital I/O signals.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The requirements for a fieldbus are therefore time-critical and cost-sensitive.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Since the new millennium, a number of fieldbuses based on Real-time Ethernet have been established.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] These have the potential to replace traditional fieldbuses in the long term.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] A fieldbus is an industrial network system for real-time distributed control.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] It is a way to connect instruments in a manufacturing plant.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] A fieldbus works on a network structure which typically allows daisy-chain, star, ring, branch, and tree network topologies.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Previously, computers were connected using RS-232 (serial connections) by which only two devices could communicate.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] This reduces both the length of and total number of cables required.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Furthermore, since devices that communicate through a fieldbus require a microprocessor, multiple points are typically provided by the same device.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Some fieldbus devices now support control schemes such as PID control on the device-side instead of forcing the controller to do the processing.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The most important motivation to use a fieldbus in a distributed control system is to reduce the cost for installation and maintenance of the installation without losing the high availability and reliability of the automation system.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The goal is to use a two wire cable and simple configuration for field devices from different manufacturers.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Depending on the application, the number of sensors and actuators vary from hundreds in one machine up to several thousands distributed over a large plant.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The history of the fieldbus demonstrates how these goals have been approached over time.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Arguably the precursor field bus technology is HP-IB as described in IEEE 488 in 1975.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] "It became known as the General Purpose Interface Bus (GPIB), and became a de facto standard for automated and industrial instrument control".
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The GPIB has its main application in automated measurements with instruments from different manufacturers.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] It is a parallel bus with a cable and connector with 24 wires, limited to a maximal cable length of 20 metres.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The oldest commonly used field bus technology is Bitbus.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Bitbus was created by Intel Corporation to enhance use of Multibus systems in industrial systems by separating slow i/o functions from faster memory access.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In 1983, Intel created the 8044 Bitbus microcontroller by adding field bus firmware to its existing 8051 microcontroller.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Bitbus uses EIA-485 at the physical layer, with two twisted pairs - one for data and the other for clocking and signals.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Use of SDLC at the data link layer permits 250 nodes on one segment with a total distance of 13.2 km.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Bitbus has one master node and multiple slaves, with slaves only responding to requests from the master.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Bitbus does not define routing at the network layer.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The 8044 permits only a relatively small data packet (13 bytes), but embeds an efficient set of RAC (remote access and control) tasks and the ability to develop custom RAC tasks.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In 1990, the IEEE adopted Bitbus as the Microcontroller System Serial Control Bus (IEEE-1118).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Today BITBUS is maintained by the BEUG - BITBUS European Users Group.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Office networks are not really suited for automation applications, as they lack the upper-bounded transmission delay.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] ARCNET, which was conceived as early as 1975 for office connectivity uses a token mechanism and therefore found later uses in industry.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The Manufacturing Automation Protocol (MAP) was an implementation of OSI-compliant protocols in automation technology initiated by General Motors in 1984.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] MAP became a LAN standardization proposal supported by many manufacturers and was mainly used in factory automation.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] MAP used the 10 Mbit/s IEEE 802.4 token bus as a transmission medium.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Due to its scope and complexity, MAP failed to make a big breakthrough.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] To reduce the complexity and reach faster processing with reduced resources the Enhanced Performance Architecture (EPA) MAP was developed in 1988.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] This MiniMap contains only levels 1, 2, and 7 of the Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) basic reference model.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] This shortcut was taken over by later fieldbus definitions.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The most important achievement of MAP is Manufacturing Message Specification (MMS), the application layer of MAP.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The Manufacturing Message Specification (MMS) is an international standard ISO 9506 dealing with an application protocol and services for transferring real time process data and supervisory control information between networked devices or computer applications published as a first version in 1986.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] It has been a model for many further developments in other industrial communication standardizations such as FMS for Profibus or SDO for CANopen.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] It is still in use as a possible application layer e.g. for power utility automation in the IEC 61850 standards.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In the field of manufacturing automation the requirements for a fieldbus are to support short reaction times with only a few bits or bytes to be transmitted over not more than some hundreds of meters.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In 1979 Modicon (now Schneider Electric) defined a serial bus to connect their programmable logic controllers (PLCs) called Modbus.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In its first version Modbus used a two wire cable with EIA 485 UART signals.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The protocol itself is very simple with a master/slave protocol and the number of data types are limited to those understood by PLCs at the time.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Nevertheless, Modbus is (with its Modbus-TCP version) still one of the most used industrial networks, mainly in the building automation field.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] A research project with the financial support of the German government defined in 1987 the fieldbus PROFIBUS based on the *Fieldbus Message Specification* (FMS).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In practical applications, it proved too complicated to handle in the field.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In 1994 Siemens proposed a modified application layer with the name *Decentralized Periphery* (DP) which reached a good acceptance in the manufacturing industry.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] As of 2016, the Profibus is one of the most installed fieldbuses in the world and reached 60 million installed nodes in 2018.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In 1987 Phoenix Contact developed a serial bus to connect spatially distributed inputs and outputs to a centralized controller.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The controller sends one frame over a physical ring, which contains all input and output data.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The cable has 5 wires: besides the ground signal, two wires for the outgoing frame and two wires for the returning frame.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] With this cable is it possible to have the whole installation in a tree topology.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The INTERBUS was very successful in the manufacturing industry with more than 22,9 million devices installed in the field.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The Interbus joined the Profinet technology for Ethernet-based fieldbus Profinet and the INTERBUS is now maintained by the Profibus Nutzerorganisation e.V.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] During the 1980s, to solve communication problems between different control systems in cars, the German company Robert Bosch GmbH first developed the Controller Area Network (CAN).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The concept of CAN was that every device can be connected by a single set of wires, and every device that is connected can freely exchange data with any other device.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] CAN soon migrated into the factory automation marketplace (with many others).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In process automation traditionally most of the field transmitters are connected over a current loop with 4-20 mA to the controlling device.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] This allows not only to transmit the measured value with the level of the current, but also provide the required electrical power to the field device with just one two-wire cable of a length of more than a thousand meters.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] These systems are also installed in hazardous areas.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] According to NAMUR a fieldbus in these applications has to fulfill these requirements.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] A special standard for instrumentation, IEC/EN 60079-27, describes requirements for the Fieldbus Intrinsically Safe Concept (FISCO) for installations in zone 0, 1 or 2.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The FIP standard is based on a French initiative in 1982 to create a requirements analysis for a future field bus standard.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The study led to the European Eureka initiative for a field bus standard in June 1986 that included 13 partners.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The development group (réseaux locaux industriels) created the first proposal to be standardized in France.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The name of the FIP field bus was originally given as an abbreviation of the French "Flux d'Information vers le Processus" while later referring to FIP with the English name "Factory Instrumentation Protocol".
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] FIP has lost ground to Profibus which came to prevail the market in Europe in the following decade - the WorldFIP homepage has seen no press release since 2002.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The closest cousin of the FIP family can be found today in the Wire Train Bus for train coaches.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] However a specific subset of WorldFIP - known the FIPIO protocol - can be found widely in machine components.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus was developed over a period of many years by the International Society of Automation (ISA) as SP50.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus today enjoys a growing installed base in many heavy process applications such as refining, petrochemicals, power generation, and even food and beverage, pharmaceuticals, and nuclear applications.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Effective January 1, 2015, the Fieldbus Foundation has become part of the new FieldComm Group.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Profibus PA (process automation) is used for communication between measuring and process instruments, actuators and process control system or PLC/DCS in process engineering.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Profibus PA is a Profibus version with physical layer suitable for process automation, in which several segments (PA segments) with field instruments can be connected to Profibus DP via so-called couplers.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The two-wire bus cable of these segments takes over not only the communication, but also the power supply of the participants (MBP transmission technology).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Another special feature of Profibus PA is the widely used device profile "PA Devices" (PA Profile), in which the most important functions of the field devices are standardized across manufacturers.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The BatiBUS defined in 1989 and used mainly in France, the Instabus extended to the European Installation Bus (EIB) and the European Home Systems Protocol (EHS) merged in 1999 to the Konnex) (KNX) standard EN 50090, (ISO/IEC 14543-3).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In 2020 495 Member companies offer 8'000 products with KNX interfaces in 190 countries worldwide.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Going back to the 1980s, unlike other networks, LonWorks is the result of the work of computer scientists from Echelon Corporation.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In 1999 the communications protocol (then known as LonTalk) was submitted to ANSI and accepted as a standard for control networking (ANSI/CEA-709.1-B), in 2005 as EN 14908 (European building automation standard).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The protocol is also one of several data link/physical layers of the BACnet ASHRAE/ANSI standard for building automation.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The BACnet standard was initially developed and is now maintained by the American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE) starting in 1987.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] BACnet is an American National Standard (ANSI) 135 since 1995, a European standard, a national standard in many countries, and global ISO Standard 16484 since 2003.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] BACnet has in 2017 a market share of 60% in building automation market.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Although fieldbus technology has been around since 1988, with the completion of the ISA S50.02 standard, the development of the international standard took many years.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In 1999, the IEC SC65C/WG6 standards committee met to resolve difference in the draft IEC fieldbus standard.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The result of this meeting was the initial form of the IEC 61158 standard with eight different protocol sets called "Types".
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] This form of standard was first developed for the European Common Market, concentrates less on commonality, and achieves its primary purpose—elimination of restraint of trade between nations.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Issues of commonality are now left to the international consortia that support each of the fieldbus standard types.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Almost as soon as it was approved, the IEC standards development work ceased and the committee was dissolved.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] A new IEC committee SC65C/MT-9 was formed to resolve the conflicts in form and substance within the more than 4000 pages of IEC 61158.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The work on the above protocol types is substantially complete.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] New protocols, such as for safety fieldbuses or real-time Ethernet fieldbuses are being accepted into the definition of the international fieldbus standard during a typical 5-year maintenance cycle.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In the 2008 version of the standard, the fieldbus types are reorganized into Communication Profile Families (CPFs).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] There were many competing technologies for fieldbuses and the original hope for one single unified communications mechanism has not been realized.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] This should not be unexpected since fieldbus technology needs to be implemented differently in different applications; automotive fieldbuses are functionally different from process plant control fieldbuses.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In June 1999 the IEC's Committee of Action (CA) decided to take a new structure for the fieldbus standards beginning with a first edition valid at the January 1, 2000, in time for the new millennium: There is a large IEC 61158 standard, where all fieldbuses find their place.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The experts have decided that the structure of IEC 61158 is maintained according to different layers, divided into services and protocols.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The individual fieldbuses are incorporated into this structure as different types.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Each part still contains several thousand pages.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Therefore, these parts have been further subdivided into subparts.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The individual protocols have simply been numbered with a type.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Each protocol type thus has its own subpart if required.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In order to find the corresponding subpart of the individual parts of the IEC 61158 standard, one must know the corresponding protocol type for a specific family.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In the 2019 edition of IEC 61158 up to 26 different types of protocols are specified.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In IEC 61158 standardization, the use of brand names is avoided and replaced by dry technical terms and abbreviations.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] For example, Ethernet is replaced by the technically correct CSMA/CD or a reference to the corresponding ISO standard 8802.3.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] This is also the case with fieldbus names, they all are replaced by type numbers.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The reader will therefore never find a designation such as PROFIBUS or DeviceNet in the entire IEC 61158 fieldbus standard.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In the section Compliance to IEC 61784 a complete reference table is provided.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] It is clear that this collection of fieldbus standards in IEC 61158 is not suitable for implementation.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] It must be supplemented with instructions for use.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] These instructions show how and which parts of IEC 61158 can be assembled to a functioning system.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] This assembly instruction has been compiled subsequently as IEC 61784 fieldbus profiles.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The IEC 61784 Part 1 standard with the name *Profile sets for continuous and discrete manufacturing relative to fieldbus use in industrial control systems* lists all fieldbuses which are proposed by the national standardization bodies.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Swiftnet, which is widely used in aircraft construction (Boeing), was included in the first edition of the standard.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] This later proves to be a mistake and in the 2007 edition 2 this protocol was removed from the standard.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] At the same time, the CPF 8 CC-Link, the CPF 9 HART protocol and CPF 16 SERCOS are added.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In the edition 4 in 2014 the last fieldbus CPF 19 MECHATROLINK was included into the standard.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The edition 5 in 2019 was just a maintenance revision without any new profile added.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] See List of automation protocols for fieldbuses that are not included in this standard.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Already in edition 2 of the fieldbus profile first profiles based on Ethernet as physical layer are included.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] All this new developed Real-time Ethernet (RTE) protocols are compiled in IEC 61784 Part 2 as *Additional profiles for ISO/IEC 8802 3 based communication networks in real-time applications*.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The SERCOS solution is interesting in this context.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] This network from the field of axis control had its own standard IEC 61491.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] With the introduction of the Ethernet-based solution SERCOS III, this standard has been taken apart and the communication part is integrated in IEC 61158/61784.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The application part has been integrated together with other drive solutions into a special drive standard IEC 61800-7.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In 2010, a second edition was published to include CPF 17 RAPIEnet and CPF 18 SafetyNET p.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In the third edition (2014), the Industrial Ethernet (IE) version of CC-Link was added.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The two profile families CPF 20 ADS-net and CPF 19 FL-net were added to the fourth edition in 2019.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] For details about these RTEs see the article on Industrial Ethernet.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] For functional safety, different consortia have developed different protocols for safety applications up to Safety Integrity Level 3 (SIL) according to IEC 61508 or Performance Level "e" (PL) according to ISO 13849.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] What most solutions have in common is that they are based on a *Black Channel* and can therefore be transmitted via different fieldbuses and networks.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Depending on the actual profile the safety protocol does provide measures like counters, CRCs, echo, timeout, unique sender and receiver IDs or cross check.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] SERCOS does use the *CIP safety* protocol as well.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In the third edition in 2016 the last safety profile CPF 17 SafetyNET p was added.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] A new edition 4 is expected to be published in 2021.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The standard has now 9 different safety profiles.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] They are all included and referenced in the global compliance table in the next section.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The protocol families of each brand name are called Communication Profile Family and are abbreviated as CPF with a number.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Each protocol family can now define fieldbuses, real-time Ethernet solutions, installation rules and protocols for functional safety.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] These possible profile families are laid down in IEC 61784 and compiled in the following table.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] As an example, we will search for the standards for PROFIBUS-DP.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] This belongs to the CPF 3 family and has the profile CP 3/1.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In Table 5 we find that its protocol scope is defined in IEC 61784 Part 1.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The physical interface is defined in the common 61158-2 under type 3.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The installation regulations can be found in IEC 61784-5-3 in Appendix A.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] It can be combined with the FSCP3/1 as PROFIsafe, which is defined in the IEC 61784-3-3 standard.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] To avoid the manufacturer having to list all these standards explicitly, the reference to the profile is specified in the standard.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Discrete fieldbus networks are often referred to as "device networks".
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Already in the year 2000 the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) decided that a set of *controller-device interfaces* (CDIs) will be specified by the Technical Committee TC 121 *Low-voltage switchgear and controlgear* to cover the device networks.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The amount of cabling required is much lower in fieldbus than in 4–20 mA installations.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] This is because many devices share the same set of cables in a multi-dropped fashion rather than requiring a dedicated set of cables per device as in the case of 4–20 mA devices.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Moreover, several parameters can be communicated per device in a fieldbus network whereas only one parameter can be transmitted on a 4–20 mA connection.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] A fieldbus also provides a good foundation for the creation of a predictive and proactive maintenance strategy.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The diagnostics available from fieldbus devices can be used to address issues with devices before they become critical problems.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Despite each technology sharing the generic name of fieldbus the various fieldbuses are not readily interchangeable.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The differences between them are so profound that they cannot be easily connected to each other.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] To understand the differences among fieldbus standards, it is necessary to understand how fieldbus networks are designed.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] With reference to the OSI model, fieldbus standards are determined by the physical media of the cabling, and layers one, two and seven of the reference model.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] For each technology the physical medium and the physical layer standards fully describe, in detail, the implementation of bit timing, synchronization, encoding/decoding, band rate, bus length and the physical connection of the transceiver to the communication wires.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The data link layer standard is responsible for fully specifying how messages are assembled ready for transmission by the physical layer, error handling, message-filtering and bus arbitration and how these standards are to be implemented in hardware.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] The application layer standard, in general defines how the data communication layers are interfaced to the application that wishes to communicate.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] It describes message specifications, network management implementations and response to the request from the application of services.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Layers three to six are not described in fieldbus standards.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Different fieldbuses offer different sets of features and performance.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] It is difficult to make a general comparison of fieldbus performance because of fundamental differences in data transfer methodology.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] In the comparison table below it is simply noted if the fieldbus in question typically supports data update cycles of 1 millisecond or faster.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] As of 2008, in process control systems, the market is dominated by Foundation Fieldbus and Profibus PA.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Both technologies use the same physical layer (2-wire Manchester-encoded current modulation at 31.25 kHz) but are not interchangeable.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] As a general guide, applications which are controlled and monitored by programmable logic controllers (PLCs) tend towards PROFIBUS, and applications which are controlled and monitored by a digital/distributed control system (DCS) tend towards Foundation Fieldbus.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] PROFIBUS technology is made available through Profibus International with headquarters in Karlsruhe, Germany.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus technology is owned and distributed by the Fieldbus Foundation of Austin, Texas.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/foundation-fieldbus] It is targeted for applications using basic and advanced regulatory control, and for much of the discrete control associated with those functions.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/foundation-fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus technology is mostly used in process industries, but has recently been implemented in powerplants.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/foundation-fieldbus] Two related implementations of Foundation Fieldbus have been introduced to meet different needs within the process automation environment.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/foundation-fieldbus] These two implementations use different physical media and communication speeds.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/foundation-fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus was originally intended as a replacement for the 4-20 mA standard, and today it coexists alongside other technologies such as Modbus, Profibus, and Industrial Ethernet.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/foundation-fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus was developed over a period of many years by the International Society of Automation, or ISA, as SP50.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/foundation-fieldbus] In 1996 the first H1 (31.25 kbit/s) specifications were released.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/foundation-fieldbus] In 1999 the first HSE (High Speed Ethernet) specifications were released.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/foundation-fieldbus] The International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) standard on field bus, including Foundation Fieldbus, is IEC 61158.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/foundation-fieldbus] Type 1 is Foundation Fieldbus H1, while Type 5 is Foundation Fieldbus HSE.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/function-block-diagram] The **function block diagram** (**FBD**) is a graphical language for programmable logic controller design, that can describe the function between input variables and output variables.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/function-block-diagram] A function is described as a set of elementary blocks.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/function-block-diagram] Input and output variables are connected to blocks by connection lines.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/function-block-diagram] Inputs and outputs of the blocks are wired together with connection lines or links.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/function-block-diagram] The connection is oriented, meaning that the line carries associated data from the left end to the right end.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/function-block-diagram] The left and right ends of the connection line must be of the same type.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/function-block-diagram] Multiple right connection, also called divergence, can be used to broadcast information from its left end to each of its right ends.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/function-block-diagram] All ends of the connection must be of the same type.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/function-block-diagram] Function Block Diagram is one of five languages for logic or control configuration supported by standard IEC 61131-3 for a control system such as a programmable logic controller (PLC) or a Distributed Control System (DCS).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/function-block-diagram] The other supported languages are ladder logic, sequential function chart, structured text, and instruction list.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Instrumentation can refer to devices as simple as direct-reading thermometers, or as complex as multi-sensor components of industrial control systems.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Instruments can be found in laboratories, refineries, factories and vehicles, as well as in everyday household use (e.g., smoke detectors and thermostats).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Measuring devices are known as a "meter" and specific types are suffixed "-meter" (such as thermometer, speedometer) in all variants of English.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] The history of instrumentation can be divided into several phases.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Elements of industrial instrumentation have long histories.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Scales for comparing weights and simple pointers to indicate position are ancient technologies.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Some of the earliest measurements were of time.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] One of the oldest water clocks was found in the tomb of the ancient Egyptian pharaoh Amenhotep I, buried around 1500 BCE.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Improvements were incorporated in the clocks.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] By 270 BCE they had the rudiments of an automatic control system device.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] In 1663 Christopher Wren presented the Royal Society with a design for a "weather clock".
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] A drawing shows meteorological sensors moving pens over paper driven by clockwork.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Such devices did not become standard in meteorology for two centuries.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] The concept has remained virtually unchanged as evidenced by pneumatic chart recorders, where a pressurized bellows displaces a pen.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Integrating sensors, displays, recorders, and controls was uncommon until the industrial revolution, limited by both need and practicality.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Early systems used direct process connections to local control panels for control and indication, which from the early 1930s saw the introduction of pneumatic transmitters and automatic 3-term (PID) controllers.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] The ranges of pneumatic transmitters were defined by the need to control valves and actuators in the field.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Typically, a signal ranged from 3 to 15 psi (20 to 100kPa or 0.2 to 1.0 kg/cm2) as a standard, was standardized with 6 to 30 psi occasionally being used for larger valves.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Transistor electronics enabled wiring to replace pipes, initially with a range of 20 to 100mA at up to 90V for loop powered devices, reducing to 4 to 20mA at 12 to 24V in more modern systems.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] A transmitter is a device that produces an output signal, often in the form of a 4–20 mA electrical current signal, although many other options using voltage, frequency, pressure, or ethernet are possible.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] The transistor was commercialized by the mid-1950s.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Instruments attached to a control system provided signals used to operate solenoids, valves, regulators, circuit breakers, relays and other devices.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Such devices could control a desired output variable, and provide either remote monitoring or automated control capabilities.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Each instrument company introduced their own standard instrumentation signal, causing confusion until the 4–20 mA range was used as the standard electronic instrument signal for transmitters and valves.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] This signal was eventually standardized as ANSI/ISA S50, "Compatibility of Analog Signals for Electronic Industrial Process Instruments", in the 1970s.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] The transformation of instrumentation from mechanical pneumatic transmitters, controllers, and valves to electronic instruments reduced maintenance costs as electronic instruments were more dependable than mechanical instruments.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] This also increased efficiency and production due to their increase in accuracy.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Pneumatics enjoyed some advantages, being favored in corrosive and explosive atmospheres.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] In the early years of process control, process indicators and control elements such as valves were monitored by an operator, that walked around the unit adjusting the valves to obtain the desired temperatures, pressures, and flows.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] As technology evolved pneumatic controllers were invented and mounted in the field that monitored the process and controlled the valves.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] This reduced the amount of time process operators needed to monitor the process.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Latter years, the actual controllers were moved to a central room and signals were sent into the control room to monitor the process and outputs signals were sent to the final control element such as a valve to adjust the process as needed.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] These controllers and indicators were mounted on a wall called a control board.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] The operators stood in front of this board walking back and forth monitoring the process indicators.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] This again reduced the number and amount of time process operators were needed to walk around the units.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] The most standard pneumatic signal level used during these years was 3–15 psig.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] However, this required a large manpower resource to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] The next logical development was the transmission of all plant measurements to a permanently staffed central control room.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Effectively this was the centralization of all the localized panels, with the advantages of lower manning levels and easy overview of the process.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] With coming of electronic processors and graphic displays it became possible to replace these discrete controllers with computer-based algorithms, hosted on a network of input/output racks with their own control processors.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] The distributed control concept was born.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] The introduction of DCSs and SCADA allowed easy interconnection and re-configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and easy interfacing with other production computer systems.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] In some cases, the sensor is a very minor element of the mechanism.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Digital cameras and wristwatches might technically meet the loose definition of instrumentation because they record and/or display sensed information.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Under most circumstances neither would be called instrumentation, but when used to measure the elapsed time of a race and to document the winner at the finish line, both would be called instrumentation.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] A very simple example of an instrumentation system is a mechanical thermostat, used to control a household furnace and thus to control room temperature.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] A typical unit senses temperature with a bi-metallic strip.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] It displays temperature by a needle on the free end of the strip.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] It activates the furnace by a mercury switch.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] As the switch is rotated by the strip, the mercury makes physical (and thus electrical) contact between electrodes.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Another example of an instrumentation system is a home security system.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Such a system consists of sensors (motion detection, switches to detect door openings), simple algorithms to detect intrusion, local control (arm/disarm) and remote monitoring of the system so that the police can be summoned.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Communication is an inherent part of the design.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Kitchen appliances use sensors for control.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Modern automobiles have complex instrumentation.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] In addition to displays of engine rotational speed and vehicle linear speed, there are also displays of battery voltage and current, fluid levels, fluid temperatures, distance traveled, and feedback of various controls (turn signals, parking brake, headlights, transmission position).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Cautions may be displayed for special problems (fuel low, check engine, tire pressure low, door ajar, seat belt unfastened).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Problems are recorded so they can be reported to diagnostic equipment.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Navigation systems can provide voice commands to reach a destination.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Automotive instrumentation must be cheap and reliable over long periods in harsh environments.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] There may be independent airbag systems that contain sensors, logic and actuators.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Anti-skid braking systems use sensors to control the brakes, while cruise control affects throttle position.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] A wide variety of services can be provided via communication links on the OnStar system.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Autonomous cars (with exotic instrumentation) have been shown.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] "Steam gauges" converted air pressures into needle deflections that could be interpreted as altitude and airspeed.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] A magnetic compass provided a sense of direction.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] The displays to the pilot were as critical as the measurements.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] A modern aircraft has a far more sophisticated suite of sensors and displays, which are embedded into avionics systems.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] The aircraft may contain inertial navigation systems, global positioning systems, weather radar, autopilots, and aircraft stabilization systems.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Redundant sensors are used for reliability.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] A subset of the information may be transferred to a crash recorder to aid mishap investigations.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Modern pilot displays now include computer displays including head-up displays.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Air traffic control radar is a distributed instrumentation system.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] The ground part sends an electromagnetic pulse and receives an echo (at least).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Aircraft carry transponders that transmit codes on reception of the pulse.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] The system displays an aircraft map location, an identifier and optionally altitude.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] The map location is based on sensed antenna direction and sensed time delay.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] The other information is embedded in the transponder transmission.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Among the possible uses of the term is a collection of laboratory test equipment controlled by a computer through an IEEE-488 bus (also known as GPIB for General Purpose Instrument Bus or HPIB for Hewlitt Packard Instrument Bus).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Laboratory equipment is available to measure many electrical and chemical quantities.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Such a collection of equipment might be used to automate the testing of drinking water for pollutants.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Instrumentation engineering is loosely defined because the required tasks are very domain dependent.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] An expert in the biomedical instrumentation of laboratory rats has very different concerns than the expert in rocket instrumentation.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Common concerns of both are the selection of appropriate sensors based on size, weight, cost, reliability, accuracy, longevity, environmental robustness, and frequency response.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Some sensors are literally fired in artillery shells.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Others sense thermonuclear explosions until destroyed.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Invariably sensor data must be recorded, transmitted or displayed.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Recording rates and capacities vary enormously.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Transmission can be trivial or can be clandestine, encrypted and low power in the presence of jamming.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Displays can be trivially simple or can require consultation with human factors experts.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Control system design varies from trivial to a separate specialty.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Instrumentation engineers are responsible for integrating the sensors with the recorders, transmitters, displays or control systems, and producing the Piping and instrumentation diagram for the process.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] They may design or specify installation, wiring and signal conditioning.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] They may be responsible for commissioning, calibration, testing and maintenance of the system.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] In a research environment it is common for subject matter experts to have substantial instrumentation system expertise.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] An astronomer knows the structure of the universe and a great deal about telescopes – optics, pointing and cameras (or other sensing elements).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] That often includes the hard-won knowledge of the operational procedures that provide the best results.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] For example, an astronomer is often knowledgeable of techniques to minimize temperature gradients that cause air turbulence within the telescope.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Instrumentation technologists, technicians and mechanics specialize in troubleshooting, repairing and maintaining instruments and instrumentation systems.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Ralph Müller (1940) stated, "That the history of physical science is largely the history of instruments and their intelligent use is well known.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] The broad generalizations and theories which have arisen from time to time have stood or fallen on the basis of accurate measurement, and in several instances new instruments have had to be devised for the purpose.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] There is little evidence to show that the mind of modern man is superior to that of the ancients.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Davis Baird has argued that the major change associated with Floris Cohen's identification of a "fourth big scientific revolution" or more often known as Fourth Industrial Revolution after World War II is the development of scientific instrumentation, not only in chemistry but across the sciences.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] In chemistry, the introduction of new instrumentation in the 1940s was "nothing less than a scientific and technological revolution" in which classical wet-and-dry methods of structural organic chemistry were discarded, and new areas of research opened up.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] Wildhack discussed both the productive and destructive potential inherent in process control.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] The ability to make precise, verifiable and reproducible measurements of the natural world, at levels that were not previously observable, using scientific instrumentation, has "provided a different texture of the world".
[src:foundation-fieldbus/instrumentation] This instrumentation revolution fundamentally changes human abilities to monitor and respond, as is illustrated in the examples of DDT monitoring and the use of UV spectrophotometry and gas chromatography to monitor water pollutants.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] In IPC, control theory provides the theoretical framework to understand system dynamics, predict outcomes and design control strategies to ensure predetermined objectives, utilizing concepts like feedback loops, stability analysis and controller design.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] On the other hand, the physical apparatus of IPC, based on automation technologies, consists of several components.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Firstly, a network of sensors continuously measure various process variables (such as temperature, pressure, etc.) and product quality variables.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] This creates a continuous closed-loop cycle of measurement, comparison, control action, and re-evaluation which guarantees that the process remains within established parameters.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] The HMI (Human-Machine Interface) acts as the "control panel" for the IPC system where small number of human operators can monitor the process and make informed decisions regarding adjustments.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] IPCs can range from controlling the temperature and level of a single process vessel (controlled environment tank for mixing, separating, reacting, or storing materials in industrial processes.) to a complete chemical processing plant with several thousand control feedback loops.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] IPC provides several critical benefits to manufacturing companies.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] By maintaining a tight control over key process variables, it helps reduce energy use, minimize waste and shorten downtime for peak efficiency and reduced costs.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] It ensures consistent and improved product quality with little variability, which satisfies the customers and strengthens the company's reputation.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] It improves safety by detecting and alerting human operators about potential issues early, thus preventing accidents, equipment failures, process disruptions and costly downtime.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Analyzing trends and behaviors in the vast amounts of data collected real-time helps engineers identify areas of improvement, refine control strategies and continuously enhance production efficiency using a data-driven approach.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] IPC is used across a wide range of industries where precise control is important.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] The applications can range from controlling the temperature and level of a single process vessel, to a complete chemical processing plant with several thousand control loops.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] In automotive manufacturing, IPC ensures consistent quality by meticulously controlling processes like welding and painting.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Mining operations are optimized with IPC monitoring ore crushing and adjusting conveyor belt speeds for maximum output.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Dredging benefits from precise control of suction pressure, dredging depth and sediment discharge rate by IPC, ensuring efficient and sustainable practices.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Pulp and paper production leverages IPC to regulate chemical processes (e.g., pH and bleach concentration) and automate paper machine operations to control paper sheet moisture content and drying temperature for consistent quality.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] In chemical plants, it ensures the safe and efficient production of chemicals by controlling temperature, pressure and reaction rates.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Oil refineries use it to smoothly convert crude oil into gasoline and other petroleum products.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] In power plants, it helps maintain stable operating conditions necessary for a continuous electricity supply.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] In food and beverage production, it helps ensure consistent texture, safety and quality.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Pharmaceutical companies relies on it to produce life-saving drugs safely and effectively.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] The development of large industrial process control systems has been instrumental in enabling the design of large high volume and complex processes, which could not be otherwise economically or safely operated.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Early process control breakthroughs came most frequently in the form of water control devices.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Ktesibios of Alexandria is credited for inventing float valves to regulate water level of water clocks in the 3rd century BC.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] In the 1st century AD, Heron of Alexandria invented a water valve similar to the fill valve used in modern toilets.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Later process controls inventions involved basic physics principles.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] In 1620, Cornelis Drebbel invented a bimetallic thermostat for controlling the temperature in a furnace.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] In 1681, Denis Papin discovered the pressure inside a vessel could be regulated by placing weights on top of the vessel lid.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] In 1745, Edmund Lee created the fantail to improve windmill efficiency; a fantail was a smaller windmill placed 90° of the larger fans to keep the face of the windmill pointed directly into the oncoming wind.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] With the dawn of the Industrial Revolution in the 1760s, process controls inventions were aimed to replace human operators with mechanized processes.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] In 1784, Oliver Evans created a water-powered flourmill which operated using buckets and screw conveyors.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Henry Ford applied the same theory in 1910 when the assembly line was created to decrease human intervention in the automobile production process.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] For continuously variable process control it was not until 1922 that a formal control law for what we now call PID control or three-term control was first developed using theoretical analysis, by Russian American engineer Nicolas Minorsky.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Minorsky was researching and designing automatic ship steering for the US Navy and based his analysis on observations of a helmsman.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] He noted the helmsman steered the ship based not only on the current course error, but also on past error, as well as the current rate of change; this was then given a mathematical treatment by Minorsky.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] His goal was stability, not general control, which simplified the problem significantly.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] While proportional control provided stability against small disturbances, it was insufficient for dealing with a steady disturbance, notably a stiff gale (due to steady-state error), which required adding the integral term.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Finally, the derivative term was added to improve stability and control.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] However this required a large manpower resource to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Effectively this was the centralization of all the localized panels, with the advantages of lower manning levels and easier overview of the process.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] These could be distributed around the plant, and communicate with the graphic display in the control room or rooms.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] The distributed control system (DCS) was born.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] The accompanying diagram is a general model which shows functional manufacturing levels in a large process using processor and computer-based control.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] To determine the fundamental model for any process, the inputs and outputs of the system are defined differently than for other chemical processes.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] The balance equations are defined by the control inputs and outputs rather than the material inputs.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] The control model is a set of equations used to predict the behavior of a system and can help determine what the response to change will be.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] The state variable (x) is a measurable variable that is a good indicator of the state of the system, such as temperature (energy balance), volume (mass balance) or concentration (component balance).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Input variable (u) is a specified variable that commonly include flow rates.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] The entering and exiting flows are both considered control inputs.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] The control input can be classified as a manipulated, disturbance, or unmonitored variable.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Parameters (p) are usually a physical limitation and something that is fixed for the system, such as the vessel volume or the viscosity of the material.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Output (y) is the metric used to determine the behavior of the system.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] The control output can be classified as measured, unmeasured, or unmonitored.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Processes can be characterized as batch, continuous, or hybrid.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Batch applications require that specific quantities of raw materials be combined in specific ways for particular duration to produce an intermediate or end result.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] One example is the production of adhesives and glues, which normally require the mixing of raw materials in a heated vessel for a period of time to form a quantity of end product.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Other important examples are the production of food, beverages and medicine.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Batch processes are generally used to produce a relatively low to intermediate quantity of product per year (a few pounds to millions of pounds).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] A continuous physical system is represented through variables that are smooth and uninterrupted in time.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] The control of the water temperature in a heating jacket, for example, is an example of continuous process control.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Some important continuous processes are the production of fuels, chemicals and plastics.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Continuous processes in manufacturing are used to produce very large quantities of product per year (millions to billions of pounds).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Such controls use feedback such as in the PID controller A PID Controller includes proportional, integrating, and derivative controller functions.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Applications having elements of batch and continuous process control are often called hybrid applications.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] The fundamental building block of any industrial control system is the control loop, which controls just one process variable.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] An example is shown in the accompanying diagram, where the flow rate in a pipe is controlled by a PID controller, assisted by what is effectively a cascaded loop in the form of a valve servo-controller to ensure correct valve positioning.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Some large systems may have several hundreds or thousands of control loops.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] In complex processes the loops are interactive, so that the operation of one loop may affect the operation of another.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] The system diagram for representing control loops is a Piping and instrumentation diagram.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Commonly used control systems include programmable logic controller (PLC), Distributed Control System (DCS) or SCADA.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] If a control valve were used to hold level in a tank, the level controller would compare the equivalent reading of a level sensor to the level setpoint and determine whether more or less valve opening was necessary to keep the level constant.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] A cascaded flow controller could then calculate the change in the valve position.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] The economic nature of many products manufactured in batch and continuous processes require highly efficient operation due to thin margins.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] The competing factor in process control is that products must meet certain specifications in order to be satisfactory.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] These specifications can come in two forms: a minimum and maximum for a property of the material or product, or a range within which the property must be.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] All loops are susceptible to disturbances and therefore a buffer must be used on process set points to ensure disturbances do not cause the material or product to go out of specifications.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] This buffer comes at an economic cost (i.e. additional processing, maintaining elevated or depressed process conditions, etc.).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Process efficiency can be enhanced by reducing the margins necessary to ensure product specifications are met.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] This can be done by improving the control of the process to minimize the effect of disturbances on the process.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] The efficiency is improved in a two step method of narrowing the variance and shifting the target.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Margins can be narrowed through various process upgrades (i.e. equipment upgrades, enhanced control methods, etc.).
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Once margins are narrowed, an economic analysis can be done on the process to determine how the set point target is to be shifted.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Less conservative process set points lead to increased economic efficiency.
[src:foundation-fieldbus/process-control] Effective process control strategies increase the competitive advantage of manufacturers who employ them.
